node.text:
How about some colorful and delicious Sweet and Sour Stir-Fry for dinner tonight! Homemade sweet and sour sauce not only tastes much better in my opinion but you’re also in control of how much and what kind of sweetener you want to use. And of course no wanted additives! 
I used soy curls for this recipe but you can make it with tofu, tempeh, chickpeas, or just veggies!
_____________________________

Sweet and Sour Sauce 

1/2 cup pineapple juice 
1/2 cup chopped pineapple 
1/4 cup tomato paste (single concentrated)
1/4 cup rice vinegar 
1/4 cup maple syrup (less to preference) 
1 small piece of ginger (about 1/2 tbsp grated) 
A couple of garlic cloves 
2 tbsp coconut aminos or light soy sauce
2 tbsp corn starch 
1 cup of water
Plus:
Salt to taste 
Ground chili flakes (optional) 

Add all ingredients to a blender, and blend until smooth.
Bring sauce to a boil in a small sauce pan, stirring continuously until it has thickened. Add additional salt to preference, and chili for some extra kick. 

You can also use coconut or another type of sugar instead of maple syrup. 
If needed, add more water to thin out the sauce. 

Add sauce to your stir-fry, or use as a dipping sauce for spring rolls etc. 
Store remaining sauce in the fridge. 
Enjoy! 

For the Stir-Fry I used: 
1 cup Soy curls (check my soy curl reel to see my favorite way to prepare them) 
Broccoli
Multi-colored peppers
Carrot
Sweet onion 
Chopped pineapple 
1/2 tbsp coconut oil 
Served over jasmine rice

Today we’re making super easy, delicious Spinach and Feta Phyllo Rolls 💚

Easy to prepare, flaky, cheesy, savory, so so yum! 
I served them with a lemony yogurt garlic dip, kind of like tzatziki but without the cucumber 🙃. 
They’d go great with a Greek salad or my Red Lentil Soup as well! 

You need: 
1 roll phyllo pastry sheets
(1/2 of the Athens Foods phyllo dough package) 
16 oz frozen spinach, chopped 
1 small sweet onion
2-3 garlic cloves 
Juice or 1 small lemon 
Salt and pepper to taste 
1/2 tbsp olive oil
4-6 oz of vegan feta cheese, crumbled with a fork (I used @violife_foods) 

Sauce: 
1/3 cup plain unsweetened non-dairy yogurt (I used @kitehillfoods ) 
2 tbsp unsweetened plant milk 
2 tbsp olive oil 

Plus: 
Plant milk or olive oil for brushing
Sesame and nigella (black cumin) seeds 

Method:
Finely dice onion, and mince garlic. 
Sauté onion until translucent, then add garlic and cook until fragrant. Add frozen spinach, and cook until heated through. Season with lemon juice, salt and pepper. 
Stir together all ingredients for the sauce. 
Brush each phyllo sheet carefully with a thin layer of the yogurt sauce, then add a spoonful of spinach and some crumbled feta. 
Roll sheet into a log, twist log into a roll, and place it on a lined baking sheet. Repeat this step with remaining pastry and filling. 
Brush finished rolls with some plant milk (or oil), sprinkle with sesame and nigella seeds, and bake at 425 F for 15-18 minutes until golden. 
Enjoy!

Treat yourself to my favorite breakfast, brunch or sometimes even lunch or (lazy no cook) dinner combo this weekend! 

Toasted fresh sourdough, with extra creamy hummus, a vegan cheese and spinach omelette (made with @justegg and @fieldroast Chao cheese), crispy spiced chickpeas, cherry tomatoes, arugula, a sprinkle of everything but the bagel seasoning, and a drizzle of balsamic glaze. 
Creamy, crunchy, savory, super satisfying and delicious! 😍

I’m currently couch bound with a sprained ankle (tripped over a kettlebell at the gym 🥴) but hopefully I’ll be able to shoot new recipes for you next week!

Wishing everyone a good weekend!

Tip: I always make a large batch of chickpeas (cooked from dry in a pressure cooker), take away about half of them after their regular cooking time (to make crispy oven-baked chickpeas, curries, chickpea salad etc.), and “over” cook the ones I need for hummus for the creamiest result!

I don’t know about you but this week calls for some real comfort food. And what’s better than a delicious bowl of creamy Pasta alla Vodka 😍
Fun fact: Despite being from Europe I had never even heard of vodka sauce before my first ever visit to New Jersey! 
Vodka actually helps intensify the flavors (despite being pretty flavor neutral), balances out the acid but also the sweetness of tomatoes and the cashew cream, and overall helps to achieve a creamier sauce. Don’t want to use vodka? Skip it or add a splash of white wine vinegar or lemon water. It’s still a tasty, creamy tomato sauce! 

Ingredients: 
1 16 oz (~500 g) package of pasta 
1 cup cashews, soaked with hot water easier blending 
1/3 cup tomato paste* 
1/2 cup vodka 
14 oz (400 g) canned tomatoes, crushed or chopped
1 tbsp olive oil
2-3 shallots or 1 small sweet onion 
3 large garlic cloves
A pinch of red pepper flakes (more to taste) 
1 tsp raw cane sugar (or other sweetener of choice) 
2 cups of pasta water
A handful of fresh basil
1/4 cup vegan parmesan (optional) 

Method:
Soak cashews with hot water for 30 minutes, then drain. If you have a high powered blender like the Vitamix you can omit this step. 
Cook pasta al dente in salted water, and reserve 2 cups of pasta water before draining. 
Finely mince shallot and garlic, and sauté both with olive oil until fragrant. Add tomato paste, and stir for a minute, then add vodka, canned tomatoes, sugar, and chili flakes.
Bring to a boil and simmer for 8-10 minutes. 
Blend soaked cashews with 1 cup of pasta water until very smooth. 
Stir cashew cream into your tomato sauce, simmer for a couple more minutes, then add hot pasta and vegan parmesan if using. 
If needed add more of the pasta water.
Top with fresh basil, and enjoy! ❤️

*not the double/triple concentrated kind

This Creamy Mushrooms with Sun-dried Tomatoes, Cannellini Beans and Spinach dish is one of my most popular and one of my personal favorite recipes this year! 

And as you can see….it’s really easy to prepare, requires only 10 main ingredients, and it’s a One-Pot recipe. 

Bonus: It’s super versatile! Enjoy it as soup with a piece of crusty bread, or serve it with pasta, gnocchi, rice, or (mashed) potatoes. 

Either way, it’s really delicious and I’d say a must try for all mushroom lovers! 🍄 

You can find the ingredient list and recipe on my feed 👇🏼and 
I’ll also link the post in a story highlight. 
 
Happy cooking! 

Tip: I recommend using extra creamy oat milk for best results! (My go to are either @chobani or @oatly )

Fresh corn season is coming to an end soon, so I’d say let’s make more delicious Corn Chowder this weekend! 🌽 
It’s an easy to prepare One-Pot dish, hearty, creamy, and really delicious! 
I used bicolor corn for mine cause it’s my favorite! Can’t get your hands on fresh corn?Just use frozen corn instead. Happy Friday everyone ☀️ 

Ingredients: 
4 ears of corn, husk and silk removed (~4 cups) 
2 medium russet potatoes (~2 cups chopped)
1 small red bell pepper 
1 jalapeño (seeded for less spice) 
1 small sweet onion (~1/2 cup) 
2-3 garlic cloves 
1 heaping tbsp vegan butter 
1 can of coconut milk * (light or regular) 
4 cups of vegetable broth (I use vegan no chicken bouillon)
1 bay leaf 
A sprig of thyme 
Salt and black/cayenne pepper to taste 

Optional: 
Fresh chives 
Crusty bread 

Method:
Prepare corn, and cut off the kernels. 
Finely dice onion, garlic, jalapeño, and bell pepper. 
Peel potatoes, and cut them into small pieces. 
Heat up butter, and sauté diced onion for about 5 minutes, then add garlic, jalapeño and bell pepper, and sauté for a few more minutes.
Add corn, potatoes, veggie broth, bay leaf and thyme. 
Bring to a boil, and simmer for 10 minutes or until potatoes are soft. Discard bay leaf and sprig, and stir in the coconut (or extra creamy oat) milk. 
Add about half of the chowder to a blender, mix until smooth, then pour it back into the pot. 
You can also use an immersion blender instead, or blend the entire batch if you prefer an extra creamy chowder. 
The chowder will thicken as it cools. 
Season to taste with salt and freshly ground black or cayenne pepper, and enjoy! 
(Makes 4 servings) 

Tip: Extra creamy oat milk works instead of coconut milk as well!

As promised I‘m sharing this super easy Arugula, Walnut and Basil Pesto with you today that I used for my “wonton“ tortellini. 

6 main ingredients, fresh, yummy, and ready in minutes! 

Other great recipes to use it for: Roasted Asparagus and Corn Pesto Pasta I just shared the other day, or my always popular 😋 Vegan Pesto Stuffed Grilled Cheese! 

It is also easily adjustable your preferences: 
1. Use more basil instead of arugula, another dark leafy green like kale or spinach 🌿
2. Replace walnuts with cashews, pine nuts, almonds, pistachios, sunflower of pumpkin seeds. 
3. Make it oil-free by using a handful of green olives instead of olive oil 🫒 
4. Don’t like raw garlic? Use garlic powder or roasted garlic instead 🧄 
6. I used lemon flavored olive oil here but adding 1-2 tbsp of lemon juice is another great option. Lemon juice will also help maintain a nice, green color! 🍋 

Ingredients: 
2 cups arugula (packed) 
1 cup basil (packed) 
1/2 cup chopped walnuts 
1/4 nutritional yeast (can be replaced  with vegan parmesan) 
3 garlic cloves 
2 tbsp lemon flavored olive oil 
Salt and black pepper to taste 

Add everything to a food processor and blend/pulse until combined. Makes 1 cup of pesto. 
Store in the fridge until use. 
Enjoy! 💚

Have you tried this super yummy Roasted Corn and Asparagus Pesto Penne Pasta? It’s one of my favorite (pasta) dishes this summer! Deliciously roasted, garlicky asparagus and corn, mixed with pasta, herby pesto and fresh lemon flavor….Yes please! 😍 
Bonus: You can serve it warm or cold as a pasta salad! 
_____________________________

Ingredients:
16 oz (~450g) green asparagus 
2 corn on the cobb, husk and silk removed 
2-3 tbsp olive oil 
3 garlic cloves
Salt 

16 oz. penne or pasta of choice
3/4 cup pesto 
(homemade or store-bought)
A few tbsp of pasta water 
Juice of 1 lemon 
Lemon zest (optional) 

Method:
Preheat oven to 425 F. 
Rinse asparagus, cut off the woody ends (you can also just snap them off with your fingers!), and prepare corn. 
Mince garlic very finely (or press it), and mix it with olive oil. 
Rub garlic oil all over the asparagus and corn, season with salt, and place asparagus on a lined baking sheet. Wrap corn in tin foil, and roast it for 15 minutes. 
After 15 minutes add asparagus to the oven, and roast everything for another 15 minutes. 
Note: Reduce asparagus roasting time to 10 min if the stalks are fairly thin. 
In the meantime prepare pasta according to package directions, and reserve some pasta water before draining. 
When asparagus and corn are done, slice asparagus into bite-sized pieces, and slice off the corn kernels with a sharp knife. 
Mix hot pasta with pesto, asparagus and corn, lemon juice and some of the zest. 
If needed, add pasta water, and season to taste with salt and black pepper. 
Enjoy!

Today I’ll show you one of my favorite ways to use soy curls! They’re super easy to prepare, and great for stir-fries! And unlike other vegan meat replacements they are only made with 1 ingredient! 

My tip to make them tasty and not watery and spongy: 
Once they’re rehydrated, drain them well, and pan-fry until browned before adding them to your stir-fry! 
I like to season them with coconut aminos to add flavor and help with caramelization. 

For these “Easier than Takeout Sweet and Spicy Soy Curls with Broccoli” you will need: 

2 cups soy curls, rehydrated with hot water or broth and drained 
1 head of broccoli, cut into florets 
3 garlic cloves (more to preference), minced 
1/4 cup dark soy sauce 
3 tbsp maple syrup (2 tbsp for a less sweet sauce) 
1 heaping tbsp chili onion crisp 
(sometimes I use sriracha instead) 
1 tbsp cornstarch, diluted in 1/2 cup water (cornstarch slurry) 

Optional: 
1/2 tbsp neutral cooking oil
Coconut aminos 

Plus: 
Sliced scallion greens 
Rice for serving 

Enjoy! 🥦

“I don’t like tofu because it’s so bland”. I’m sure most of us have heard (or said) it at some point. My first encounter with it wasn’t much fun either. I expected it to be feta cheese and then….well you can picture the rest haha. 
But if you pan-fry it until crispy (air frying or baking works too), and then glaze it with delicious sauce….that is a totally different story. 
Like this sweet and spicy Mango Habanero Tofu! 🥭🌶 

Mango Habanero Sauce:
1-2 ripe mangos* (about 1 cup chopped) 
2-3 habaneros
2 garlic cloves
1 small carrot, roughly chopped 
1/2 tbsp grated ginger
1/4 cup rice vinegar 
2 tbsp maple or agave syrup 
Juice of 2 limes plus a tsp of lime zest 
1/2 cup water
Salt to taste

Tofu:
1 block of super firm (also known as high protein) tofu 
A generous pinch of salt 
1-2 tbsp Cornstarch 
1 tbsp avocado oil 

Attention: Habaneros are very spicy! Take out the seeds, only use 1, replace with jalapeños or just omit completely if you’re sensitive to spice! And don’t forget to wash hands thoroughly after handling them! 

Method:
Add all ingredients for the sauce except lime juice to a blender, and blend until smooth. 
Bring sauce to a boil while whisking continuously until it thickens. Simmer for 10 minutes, stirring occasionally. Add lime juice at the end, and season to taste with salt. 
Refrigerate in a clean glass jar. 

Cut tofu in half horizontally, and pat away any moisture with a clean kitchen towel. Cut the 2 pieces into bite-sized cubes, season them with salt, and dust with cornstarch until evenly coated. I use a small sieve for that, but you can also dip the pieces in cornstarch and shake off any excess powder. 
Brush a cast iron skillet with avocado oil, bring it to medium heat, and fry tofu pieces from all sides until golden. Flip them around after 2-3 minutes on each side. 
Toss them with the mango habanero sauce (I used a little more than 1/2 a cup), and let everything cook on low heat for 5-10 minutes until every piece is evenly coated and lightly caramelized. 
Enjoy! 

*My preferred mangos are Ataulfo mangos (smallish yellow ones) which is why I need 2 of them. 

This is the same sauce I used for my cauliflower taquitos by the way.

Finding vegan-friendly tortellini (that don’t cost a fortune) can be quite tricky….so let’s make our own! 
And with this simple hack of using wonton wrappers instead of fresh pasta dough, they come together super fast! 

Disclaimer: I know these are not authentic Italian Tortellini 🙃 but my “Wontonellinis” are fun, yum, and easy to prepare! 

You only need:
Vegan wonton wrappers 
Filling/Pesto of choice 
A little bit of water 

I filled mine with a simple homemade Basil, Arugula and Walnut Pesto. Let me know if you are interested in the recipe for the pesto, and I’ll share that next! 

As you can see in the video I pan-fried the tortellini until golden, crispy and delicious!
You can of course also cook them in simmering salt water for about 5 minutes or until they float to the top, and then add them to soup or toss them with pasta sauce!

Rainy Sundays call for yummy pancakes! And since blueberries 🫐 are in season, what better way to enjoy them than in super delicious, fluffy Vanilla Oat Blueberry Pancakes with Blueberry Compote and Maple-Yogurt Syrup. The best part….while these pancakes may sound like a treat, they’re actually full of good ingredients. Happy Sunday everyone 💙
________________________

Ingredients: 
2 cups oat flour (ground oats) 
2 cups plain or vanilla plant milk
1 small ripe banana, mashed 
1 tbsp maple syrup 
1 tbsp apple cider vinegar 
1 tsp baking powder 
1 tsp baking soda 
1 tsp vanilla extract 
1/4 tsp ground vanilla pod (optional) 
Pinch of salt 
1/4 cup sparkling water (optional) 

Plus:
16 oz fresh blueberries 
1 tbsp maple syrup 

Method: 
Stir together all ingredients for the pancake batter, and let it sit for at least 20 minutes. Batter should thicken as it sits. Gently stir in sparkling water. 
This makes extra fluffy pancakes. 
You can skip this step, and your pancakes will still turn out great. If needed add an extra splash of plant milk. The batter should be thick but pourable. 
Fold in half of the blueberries, and heat up a non stick skillet. 
Bake pancakes for a 2-3 minutes each side until browned. (I always use a ladle to measure out the amount)
Flip when you see a few bubbles on the uncooked side. Use low heat to avoid burning. 
For the blueberry compote, simply add blueberries to a small saucepan with maple syrup and heat up until glossy and juicy. 
Serve over pancakes, and enjoy! 

For the maple yogurt sauce, whisk together some vegan yogurt, maple syrup and vanilla (optional) until smooth.
